<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-456-015  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 456 015.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  August 30 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>CPSR brings suit to obtain FBI records on BBS monitoring.andO;(Computer Professionals for Social Responsibility, bulletin boardsystems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer Professionals for Social ResponsibilityComputer bulletin boardsUnited States. Federal Bureau of InvestigationRecordsCourt CasesComputer crimesInvestigationsGovernment Agency.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>CPSR BRINGS SUIT TO OBTAIN FBI RECORDS ON BBS MONITORING WASHINGTON, D.C.,andO;U.S.A., 1990 AUG 30 (NB) -- Computer Professionals for Social Responsibility(CPSR) , on August 28th, filed a suit in Federal District Court to attempt toobtain information from the Federal Bureau of Investigation about themonitoring of computer bulletin boards.andM;Marc Rotenberg, director of the CPSR Washington Office, said that thedisclosure of the records would provide a starting point for an informeddiscussion about the proper scope of computer crime investigations.andP;  He saidthat the FBI's failure to respond to CPSR's original Freedom of InformationAct request made the lawsuit necessary.andM;According to the CPSR statement, &quot;The Freedom of Information Act provides alegal right for individuals to obtain records held by government agencies.andO;Under the law, agencies are required to respond within ten working days.andO;When agencies fail to respond within a reasonable period of time, requestersoften begin legal proceedings to obtain the information.andP;  CPSR filed theoriginal FOIA request in August, 1989.andP;  After a series of letters from CPSRto the FBI failed to produce a response, the FOIA request was considered at aCongressional hearing in February, 1990.andP;  A subsequent letter from theTreasury Department revealed that the Secret Service was in fact monitoringcomputer bulletin boards.andP;  The FBI's activities are still not known.&quot;andM;Rotenberg told Newsbytes, &quot;We can't determine whether the FBI practices arelawful without obtaining these records.andP;  The doubt concerning the FBIpractices has put computing freedom at risk.&quot;andM;Rotenberg when on to explain that some of the concern goes back to 1982 whengovernment documents indicate that the FBI asked for a legal opinion as towhether it could monitor bulletin boards to ascertain whether illegalactivity was going on, Rotenberg added, &quot;Although the FBI received a rulingthat it was inappropriate to perform these activities, there is some doubtthat it followed the ruling.andP;  It is only through a review of the requestedrecords that we can determine whether it was adhered to.&quot;andM;The case filed is CPSR v. FBI.andP;  Civil Action No.andP;  90-2096, U.S.andP;  DistrictCourt for the District of Columbia, August 28.andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19900829/Press Contact: MarcRotenberg, CPSR, 202-775-1588)</TEXT></DOC>